🚀 Day 08 – Debugging Pandas Column & DataFrame Issues

Python Debugging Lab (14-Day Series)

Today I focused on debugging one of the most common problems in data analysis:

👉 Pandas DataFrame column errors.

When working with datasets, many bugs happen due to incorrect column names, hidden spaces, wrong indexing, or incorrect data types.

Understanding how to inspect and debug DataFrames is essential for data professionals.


---

🔍 Topics Covered

KeyError in Pandas

Case sensitivity in column names

Hidden whitespace issues

Checking columns with df.columns

Safe column access

Understanding DataFrame structure



---

💡 Key Learning #1 – Pandas KeyError

Example:

import pandas as pd

df = pd.DataFrame({"age":[20,25,30]})
print(df["Age"])

This crashes with:

KeyError: 'Age'

Why?

Column names in Pandas are case-sensitive.

Correct version:

print(df["age"])


---

💡 Key Learning #2 – Hidden Spaces in Column Names

Sometimes datasets contain hidden spaces.

Example:

df.columns

Output might be:

Index(['Age ', 'Salary'], dtype='object')

Notice the space after "Age ".

Safe solution:

df.columns = df.columns.str.strip()

This removes unwanted spaces.


---

💡 Key Learning #3 – Always Inspect Data

Before working with a dataset, always check:

print(df.head())
print(df.columns)
print(df.info())

These commands help understand the dataset structure.


---

💡 Key Learning #4 – Safe Column Checking

Before accessing a column:

if "age" in df.columns:
    print(df["age"])

This prevents runtime errors.


---

🎯 Why This Matters

DataFrame debugging is essential because:

Real datasets often contain messy column names

Case sensitivity causes many errors

Hidden spaces break filtering and aggregation

Data inspection prevents silent bugs


Strong debugging habits make data analysis much more reliable.


